 -- Function: np_ref (A, I)
     Access a single element of an ndarray by index.

     Indices are 0-based.  For 1D arrays, pass one index.  For 2D
     arrays, pass row and column indices.

     Calling forms:

        • ‘np_ref(a, i)’ - element at position ‘i’ in a 1D array
        • ‘np_ref(a, i, j)’ - element at row ‘i’, column ‘j’ in a 2D
          array

* Menu:

     * Examples::

1.3.1.15 Examples
.................

(%i1) A : np_arange(5);
(%o1)            ndarray([5], DOUBLE-FLOAT)
(%i2) np_ref(A, 0);
(%o2)                          0.0
(%i3) np_ref(A, 3);
(%o3)                          3.0
(%i4) B : ndarray(matrix([10, 20], [30, 40]));
(%o4)            ndarray([2, 2], DOUBLE-FLOAT)
(%i5) np_ref(B, 1, 0);
(%o5)                         30.0

See also: ‘np_set’, ‘np_row’, ‘np_col’


File: numerics.info,  Node: Function np_set a i j val,  Next: Function np_row a i,  Prev: Function np_ref a i,  Up: Conversion

 -- Function: np_set (A, I, J, VAL)
     Set a single element of an ndarray (mutating).

     Indices are 0-based.  The last argument is the value to set,
     preceding arguments are indices.  The array is modified in place
     and returned.

     Calling forms:

        • ‘np_set(a, i, val)’ - set element at position ‘i’ in a 1D
          array
        • ‘np_set(a, i, j, val)’ - set element at row ‘i’, column ‘j’ in
          a 2D array

* Menu:

     * Examples::

1.3.1.16 Examples
.................

(%i1) A : np_zeros([2, 2]);
(%o1)            ndarray([2, 2], DOUBLE-FLOAT)
(%i2) np_set(A, 0, 0, 42.0);
(%o2)            ndarray([2, 2], DOUBLE-FLOAT)
(%i3) np_ref(A, 0, 0);
